<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">February 26, 2024</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-february-26-2024/"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-233580 size-thumbnail" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ice-150x150.jpeg" alt="Ice" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2024/feb/23/sigrid-nunez-when-i-was-growing-up-i-wanted-to-be-dr-seuss" class="external" target="_blank">Sigrid Nunez talks Seussian aspirations</a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://orionmagazine.org/article/gutbucket-yukon-canada-permafrost-melt/" class="external" target="_blank">Emily Raboteau considers the necessity of rituals at the end of the world</a>.</li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.nybooks.com/online/2024/02/23/who-should-regulate-online-speech-david-cole/" class="external" target="_blank">Who should regulate speech online?</a></li>
</ul>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-february-26-2024/"><button>More News</button></a></li>
